SIMPLE: loggerhead
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Loggerhead
<hw>Log"ger*head`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Log</ets>
+ <ets>head</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A blockhead; a dunce; a
numskull.</def> <rj><au>Shak. Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A spherical mass of iron, with a long handle, used
to heat tar.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>An upright piece of round timber,
in a whaleboat, over which a turn of the line is taken when it is
running out too fast.</def> <rj><au>Ham. Nav. Encyc.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A very large marine turtle
(<spn>Thalassochelys caretta</spn> syn. <spn>Thalassochelys
caouana</spn>), common in the warmer parts of the Atlantic Ocean, from
Brazil to Cape Cod; -- called also <altname>logger-headed
turtle</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>An American shrike (<spn>Lanius
Ludovicianus</spn>), similar to the butcher bird, but smaller. See
<er>Shrike</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>To be at loggerheads</b></col>, <col><b>To fall to
loggerheads</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>To go to
loggerheads</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to quarrel; to be at strife.</cd>
<au>L' Estrange.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Loggerheaded</ent>⟦br⟧
